Seven near-simultaneous bomb blasts in Jaipur killed 80 and injured 200, sparking condemnation from global leaders.
While Indian officials refrained from directly accusing Pakistan, suspicions lingered.
The attacks, reminiscent of past tragedies, reignited fears of communal violence.
The US and France pledged support in combating terrorism, emphasizing solidarity with India.
The blasts, strategically targeting crowded markets and temples, left a trail of devastation.
As authorities investigate, the nation mourns the senseless loss of life and braces for potential repercussions.
High alert status remains across key cities, underscoring the ongoing threat of terrorism.
